{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Secretogranin-2 (ScgII), a neuroendocrine secretory granule protein, is almost exclusively found in large dense core vesicles of a wide variety of endocrine and neuronal tissues. It belongs to the chromogranin family, whose members are acidic proteins present in the secretory granules of a wide variety of endocrine and neuro-endocrine cells. ScgII has been linked to several neurological diseases, like Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, epilepsy, stroke or ischemia and and diabetic retinopathy. ScgII also plays a role in visual system plasticity by modulating a range of neurotransmitters and neuropeptides [[cite:PUB00088498]].</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Secretoneurin (SN), a 33-amino acid neuropeptide derived from secretogranin II, acts as an angiogenic cytokine [[cite:PUB00088706]] and chemoattractant for eosinophils [[cite:PUB00088707]]. Manserin is another peptide derived from secretogranin II [[cite:PUB00088708]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR15119" "SECRETOGRANIN II"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Secretogranin-2", "short" "ScgII"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 617, "taxa" 2103, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1012, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1012, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 713}, "pathways" 8}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR038858", :literature {"PUB00088498" {"URL" nil, "issue" "7", "authors" ["Paulussen M" "Van Brussel L" "Arckens L."], "ISO_journal" "Neurochem. Int.", "DOI_URL" "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuint.2011.09.004", "medline_journal" "Neurochem Int", "title" "Monocular enucleation profoundly reduces secretogranin II expression in adult mouse visual cortex.", "year" 2011, "raw_pages" "1082-94", "volume" "59", "ISBN" nil, "PMID" 2